1.1 Explanation¶

Index¶

Gini(inequality):¶

Gini measures inequality: How large are the income differences within a society. First imagine you line up all people in a country, ordered by income: The poorest to the left and the richest to the right. Now you walk from the left to the right asking how much money they earn every year, and you add up the number. When you reach the middle, you have counted 50% of the people, but the richest half remains. The amount of income you have added up is much less than 50% of all the money, say , maybe 20%. Maybe 10%? If there are lots of people with low incomes, you will have added maybe 15% of the money for the poorest half of the population, but if the income differences are less extreme, the 50% poorest may earn 30% of the incomes. If everybody earns the same, you would have gotten to 50% of the money, after asking 50% of the people. In that case (which never happens), the gini is zero. No inequality. The opposite extreme case (which also never happens) would be that only the richest person has any income: one guy earns all the money. Then the gini is 1. Perfect inequality. But most countries have a gini somewhere around 0.4, in-between these two extreme examples.

https://www.gapminder.org/data/documentation/gini/

HDI (Human Development Index)¶

The HDI was created to emphasize that people and their capabilities should be the ultimate criteria for assessing the development of a country, not economic growth alone. The HDI can also be used to question national policy choices, asking how two countries with the same level of GNI per capita can end up with different human development outcomes. These contrasts can stimulate debate about government policy priorities. The Human Development Index (HDI) is a summary measure of average achievement in key dimensions of human development: a long and healthy life, being knowledgeable and have a decent standard of living. The HDI is the geometric mean of normalized indices for each of the three dimensions.

The health dimension is assessed by life expectancy at birth, the education dimension is measured by mean of years of schooling for adults aged 25 years and more and expected years of schooling for children of school entering age. The standard of living dimension is measured by gross national income per capita. The HDI uses the logarithm of income, to reflect the diminishing importance of income with increasing GNI. The scores for the three HDI dimension indices are then aggregated into a composite index using geometric mean. Refer to Technical notes for more details.

The HDI simplifies and captures only part of what human development entails. It does not reflect on inequalities, poverty, human security, empowerment, etc. The HDRO offers the other composite indices as broader proxy on some of the key issues of human development, inequality, gender disparity and poverty.

A fuller picture of a country's level of human development requires analysis of other indicators and information presented in the statistical annex of the report.

http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/human-development-index-hdi

Country types¶

IC:¶

A developed country, industrialized country (or post-industrial country), more developed country, or more economically developed country (MEDC), is a sovereign state that has a developed economy and advanced technological infrastructure relative to other less industrialized nations. Most commonly, the criteria for evaluating the degree of economic development are gross domestic product (GDP), gross national product (GNP), the per capita income, level of industrialization, amount of widespread infrastructure and general standard of living. Which criteria are to be used and which countries can be classified as being developed are subjects of debate.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Developed_country

NIC :¶

A newly industrialized country (or NIC) is a developing economy that has transitioned from being based on agriculture or extraction of raw materials, to being primarily based on the production of manufactured goods. These nations have taken important steps towards industrialization and might be considered as developed economies at some point in the near future. Sometimes, these economies are also referred to as emerging markets.

This categorization was first adopted in the second half of the 20th century, originally referring to Hong Kong, Taiwan, South Korea, and Singapore: four economies that were rapidly transforming and moving towards development thanks to high-tech manufacturing. Today, they are considered to have fully developed and are studied as the first generation of NICs.

There is not a total consensus on which nations are NICs, but most economists agree that there are nine at this point in time:

China
India
Thailand
Malaysia
Philippines
Turkey
South Africa
Brazil
Mexico

China and India represent particularly notable cases. Both nations are industrial giants, and their production surpasses many industrialized nations, but because of their large population, the average income and the overall social development remain low.

https://study.com/academy/lesson/newly-industrialized-countries-characteristics-sectors-of-production.html

LDC:¶

Least developed countries (LDCs) are low-income countries confronting severe structural impediments to sustainable development. They are highly vulnerable to economic and environmental shocks and have low levels of human assets.

There are currently 47 countries on the list of LDCs which is reviewed every three years by the Committee for Development (CDP).

LDCs have exclusive access to certain international support measures in particular in the areas of development assistance and trade. Afghanistan

Angola, Bangladesh, Benin, Bhutan, Burkina Faso, Burundi, Cambodia Central African Republic, Chad, Comoros,Democratic, Republic of the Congo, Djiboutim Eritrea, Ethiopia,Gambia, Guine, Guinea-Bissau, Haiti, Kiribati, Lao People’s Dem. https://www.un.org/development/desa/dpad/least-developed-country-category.html

For later visuals, there is a function which will compute min and max values for dataframe and computing the % change. This function get used for displaying which country increased or decreased a specific trend, more or less. For further visuals a new dataframe for only % change for each indicator and death reason will created.

Also there is a need to checkout the standard deviation variance of country categories in indicators that will investigated. I add a function that compute standard deviation by percent % column of prop_minmax function. The std variance function will then give us a indicator for variance in the country categories (IC,NIC,LDC)

In [14]:
# check if df have country columns then gives min max values and compute the difference in total and %
# if columsn are years instead of country they will be swaped by else statement.

def prop_minmax(df):
    
    if df.columns.str.isdigit().any() == True:
        dft = df.T
        minmax = dft.describe().loc[['min','max'],:,]
        diff = minmax.loc['max'] - minmax.loc['min']
        
        minmax.loc['difference'] = diff
        proc = minmax.loc['max'] / minmax.loc[['min'],:,].sum() 
        minmax.loc['procent'] = (proc -1 ) * 100
        return minmax
    else: 
        
        minmax = df.describe().loc[['min','max'],:,]
        diff = minmax.loc['max'] - minmax.loc['min']
        
        minmax.loc['difference'] = diff
        proc =  minmax.loc['difference'] / minmax.loc[['min','max'],:,].sum() 
        minmax.loc['procent'] = proc
        return minmax

# new Dataframes for % change in all data from ic,nic,ldc
# for trend values measured in min,max

s_proc = pd.DataFrame(prop_minmax(s_all).loc['procent'])

m_proc = pd.DataFrame(prop_minmax(m_all).loc['procent'])

gini_proc = pd.DataFrame(prop_minmax(gini_all).loc['procent'])

hdi_proc = pd.DataFrame(prop_minmax(hdi_all).loc['procent'])

        

    
#computing std /100 to make it a variance index for IC,NIC,LDC 
def stdvar(df):
    v = prop_minmax(df).loc['procent']
    x = np.std(v)/100
    
    return x

# computing std variance stdvar for country categories, requiers contry names as list

def varg(x):
    for i in x:
        lists = []
        
        s = stdvar(i)
        
        lists.append(s)
        
        print(lists)

3. EDA (exploratory data analysis)¶

For this notebook we will do some quick observations for outstanding trend moves and outliers. Most of the EDA and delivered statistics give a starting-point for more research.

Following visuals and index values will used in this section:

  • lineplots that gives us allover insights about rising and falling trend curves

  • color coded countries in the lineplots, see introduction above

  • variance index value from 0 to 1, gives us a indicator how much each country category (IC,NIC,LDC) varies in their % change. 0 means country trends were very low and 1 means country trends varies alot.

Inequality¶

IC´s : The allover Trend for the IC´s are lowering GINI rating, except United Kingdom who received a higher amount in inequality since 1973

  • "Economists from the group, which is funded by developed-world taxpayers, say the annual average income in the UK of the top 10% in 2008 was just under £55,000, about 12 times higher than that of the bottom 10%, who had an average income of £4,700. This is up from a ratio of eight to one in 1985 and significantly higher than the average income gap in developed nations of nine to one. However, the report makes clear that even in countries viewed as "fairer" – such as Germany, Denmark and Sweden – this pay gap between rich and poor is expanding: from five to one in the 1980s to six to one today. In the rising powers of Brazil, Russia, India and China, the ratio is an alarming 50 to one. The OECD warned about the rise of the top 1% in rich societies and the falling share of income going to poorer people." https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/dec/05/income-inequality-growing-faster-uk

Although Chinese industrialization is largely defined by its 20th-century campaigns, China has a long history that contextualizes the proto-industrial efforts, and explains the reasons for delay of industrialization in comparison to Western countries. In 1952, 83 percent of the Chinese workforce were employed in agriculture. figure remained high, but was declining steadily, throughout the early phase of industrialization between the 1960s and 1990s, but in view of the rapid population growth this amounted to a rapid growth of the industrial sector in absolute terms, of up to 11 percent per year during the period.[2][3] By 1977, the fraction of the workforce employed in agriculture had fallen to about 77 percent, and by 2012, 33 percent." https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_industrialization

Suicide rates¶

Plotting suicide rates for the three country types, on the same way as before.

LDC : China as have a overall higher amount of suicide in total so it will get excluded in the second lineplot. Although China have a high rate, it turns out HDI and GDP have a positive effect on the suicide every year. In a different view the GINI rate gets higher for china but suicide rates aren´t affected by that.

A hypothesis for higher Rates in China than in the rest of the IC,NIC,LDC´s.

  • "Easy access to the means of suicide has been discussed as the most prominent reason why suicide rates are high in China. Pesticide availability is one example. Nearly all rural households store pesticides, which makes suicide means readily available in the Chinese countryside (The Economist, 1997). Handguns, which are a primary means of suicide in the West, are not available to Chinese civilians, and account for only about 0.1% of Chinese suicides (Zhang, 1996). Although usually less violent and less efficient than guns, pesticides can be an efficient means of suicide if they are easily available and if few hospitals are equipped to treat patients who have ingested them. No reliable figures yet exist for the ratio of attempted suicides to completed suicides in China. The difference between China and other countries may lie not so much in a higher rate of attempted suicide, but in a higher rate of attempted suicides that die because of unsuccessful remedial action (The Economist, 1997)."

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2913725/

But as we can see rates are dropping hard as the "developing state" of the country is evolving even more and more. See HDI

NIC´s suicide rates have decreased for the last decades. But a recent trend is an increasing value since 2013. This trend builds up the hypothesis of the modern depression thesis in industrialized countries. The more a country gets wealthy and modern the more the depression rate increases.

  • "Robert Burton presciently implicated the quality and quantity of diet, heredity, solitude, idleness, sleep, loss/sorrow, fear, shame, envy, malice, ambition, vanity, excessive study[!], and poverty as causes of melancholy over 350 years ago (Burton, 1845). There has been much progress, but countless questions circling the concept of depression and its origins still remain unanswered. A better understanding of large-scale causes and the complex relationships between modern culture, chronic disease, and depression will be essential for systemic, population-based interventions to address a very common affliction. More research is necessary to unravel the role of specific health behaviors within individual depressive phenotypes, e.g. atypical versus melancholic depression." https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3330161/

LDC´s : For least developed countries we see a negative trend for Bangladesh with a flattening curve in 2015.

For better exploration lets take a look at mali and haiti. There is rising trend of murder rate above 67%.

4. Conclusions¶

Newly industrialized countries : They tend to have a great variance between all indicators and death reasons. China stands out because we can see big movements in trends.

CHINA:

  • decreasing murder rate by 167% and decreasing suicide rate by 90%.
  • At the same time China did increased their HDI with 47% and less suicides by 32%.
  • special thing about this is that china is alwas in the top 2 of trend changes, as we can investigate by looking at the barplots for % changes.

As conclusion we can say that the HDI and GINI did affect most of NIC´s. The great variance in every indicator gives a great view of the definition of a NIC´s; that those countries are changing with the factors a newly industrialized country have.

Industrialized countries : There is a major trend in all % changes in this country category. As we can see in the barplots, IC´s always have very low variance in their changes even if the % change is between 40% in some cases, between the IC´s eachother, they stay close in the change rate, compared with the rest of the change rates.

  • To make a conclusion, IC´s dont show much here but the overall increasing HDI and decreasing GINI rating, correlated well with all death reasons. Although suicide rates in IC´s are increasing like described in the EDA explanation.

  • the low variance in their % changes defines them as modern country with stable state

Least developed : Rising murder and sucide rates for mali and haiti. There is a negative correlation between their HDI,GINI. Allover less correlations for bangladesh. But the variance of all indicators and death reasons are mostly the
